9. Orchestrating Serverless Functions with
AWS Step Functions - simulation in
Docker

Go to labs.play-with-docker.com and perform the following tasks

Step 1: Create Folders and Basic Files
📂 1. Create project folder and move into it
mkdir project
cd project

📂 2. Create subfolders for:
● input (where you upload the source image)
● output (where resized and watermarked images will be saved)
● resize (for first container: resize image)
● watermark (for second container: add watermark)

mkdir input output resize watermark

Now your folder tree looks like this:

/project
/input
/output

/resize
/watermark

📄 3. Create resize/app.py file
cd resize
vi app.py

Type this Python code inside: (press i to insert)

from PIL import Image
import os
input_path = '/data/input/image.jpg'
output_path = '/data/output/resized.jpg'
print("Resizing image...")
image = Image.open(input_path)
image = image.resize((300, 300))
image.save(output_path)
print("Image resized and saved!")

Press Ecs, and type :wq

📄 4. Create resize/Dockerfile
vi Dockerfile

Type this inside:

(press i to insert)
FROM python:3.11-slim
RUN pip install pillow
WORKDIR /app
COPY app.py .
CMD ["python", "app.py"]

Save and exit. (Press ESC, :wq)

📄 5. Now set up watermark/app.py
Go back to project root:

cd ../watermark
(or )
cd ..
cd watermark
Now create another python file here.
vi app.py

Type this python code:

from PIL import Image, ImageDraw, ImageFont
import os
input_path = '/data/output/resized.jpg'
output_path = '/data/output/watermarked.jpg'

print("Adding watermark...")
image = Image.open(input_path)
draw = ImageDraw.Draw(image)
font = ImageFont.load_default()
draw.text((50, 50), "Sample Watermark", fill=(0, 255, 128), font=font)
image.save(output_path)
print("Watermarked image saved!")

Save and exit. (ESC, :wq)

📄 6. Create watermark/Dockerfile
You are inside the project/watermark ; Now create a Dockerfile here.
vi Dockerfile

Type this:

FROM python:3.11-slim
RUN pip install pillow
WORKDIR /app
COPY app.py .
CMD ["python", "app.py"]

Save and exit.

✅ Now your full structure looks like this:

/project

/input/
/output/
/resize/
app.py
Dockerfile
/watermark/
app.py
Dockerfile

Now Build Containers:

Build Containers
In your Play-with-Docker terminal:

cd /project
{
OR just type:
cd ..
This will take you to /projects }
# Build resize container
docker build -t resize-image ./resize
# Build watermark container
docker build -t watermark-image ./watermark

Now add the image: Type the following command:

wget -O input/image.jpg https://picsum.photos/600/400

Run Containers in Sequence (simulate Step Functions)
# Resize the image
docker run --rm -v $(pwd)/input:/data/input -v
$(pwd)/output:/data/output resize-image
# Watermark the resized image
docker run --rm -v $(pwd)/input:/data/input -v
$(pwd)/output:/data/output watermark-image

Now run the following Command:
python3 -m http.server 8080
